  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Understanding Fertility Awareness Methods (FAMs)</h1>
      <p>The science of tracking your cycle for hormone-free contraception.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">
      <p>Fertility Awareness Methods (FAMs) are natural, hormone-free ways to prevent pregnancy. They rely on understanding and tracking the physical signs of your menstrual cycle to determine which days you are fertile and which days you are not. Because an egg only lives for 12-24 hours, and sperm can live inside the body for up to 5 days, there is a specific "fertile window" during each cycle.</p>

      <p><em>Note: FAMs require dedication, daily tracking, and a high level of bodily awareness. They are not recommended for those with highly irregular cycles.</em></p>

      <h2>The Core Methods of Tracking</h2>
      <p>For the highest effectiveness (often called the Symptothermal Method), you should track multiple signs simultaneously.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>1. Basal Body Temperature (BBT)</h3>
        <p>Your basal body temperature is your body's temperature fully at rest. After ovulation, the release of progesterone causes a slight but measurable spike in your BBT (usually between 0.4 and 1.0 degrees Fahrenheit).</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>How to track:</strong> You must take your temperature every single morning immediately upon waking, before sitting up, speaking, or drinking water, using a highly precise BBT thermometer.</li>
          <li><strong>What it tells you:</strong> The temperature shift confirms that ovulation <em>has already occurred</em>. Once the temperature has stayed elevated for 3 consecutive days, the fertile window has closed.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>2. Cervical Mucus Monitoring</h3>
        <p>Hormonal fluctuations throughout your cycle change the texture and volume of your cervical mucus.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>How to track:</strong> Check the mucus on your toilet paper or by inserting clean fingers into the vagina daily.</li>
          <li><strong>What it tells you:</strong> Right after your period, you may have dry days. As ovulation approaches, mucus becomes sticky, then creamy, and finally clear, slippery, and stretchy (like raw egg whites). This "egg white" mucus indicates peak fertility.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>3. Cervical Position</h3>
        <p>The cervix changes position and texture throughout the month.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>How to track:</strong> Reach inside the vagina to feel the cervix daily.</li>
          <li><strong>What it tells you:</strong> During non-fertile times, the cervix feels low, hard (like the tip of your nose), and closed. During the fertile window, it moves higher up, feels soft (like your lips), and slightly open.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>Effectiveness and Risks</h2>
      <p>When used perfectly (tracking all signs daily without fail and abstaining from unprotected sex during the entire fertile window), the Symptothermal Method can be up to 98% effective.</p>
      <p>However, typical use effectiveness sits around 77%. The main risks include:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Human error in taking measurements (e.g., waking up late, being sick, or drinking alcohol can skew BBT).</li>
        <li>Misinterpreting the signs of cervical mucus.</li>
        <li>Taking risks and having unprotected sex on a "borderline" day.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Using Technology: Apps and Devices</h2>
      <p>While traditional charting on paper works well, many people use apps to log their data. Be extremely cautious: do not rely on apps that merely predict ovulation based on calendar averages. Use apps that act as a diary for your BBT and mucus inputs, allowing you to interpret the data or using a certified algorithm to calculate the window based strictly on your daily biological inputs.</p>

